      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18275870-first-night-of-summer">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">fans of thrillers and crime stories</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer704839446" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2079603930128469624">There was a story in the news recently about a couple who had abused and eventually murdered their young child. Many of my friends and family expressed their shock and disgust with the couple, sharing such sentiments as &quot;they don&apos;t deserve a trial, they should be taken outside and shot&quot;. Similarly, during rape cases, I have heard the hope expressed that the rapist would in turn be raped in prison, to experience the same horror as his victims.<br/><br/>This kind of thinking frightens me. To me, the idea th</span>
  <span id="freeText2079603930128469624" style="display:none">There was a story in the news recently about a couple who had abused and eventually murdered their young child. Many of my friends and family expressed their shock and disgust with the couple, sharing such sentiments as "they don't deserve a trial, they should be taken outside and shot". Similarly, during rape cases, I have heard the hope expressed that the rapist would in turn be raped in prison, to experience the same horror as his victims.<br /><br />This kind of thinking frightens me. To me, the idea that violent behaviour should be met with more violent behaviour makes no sense. The rapist and the person who wishes he gets raped have exactly the same mentality, it's just a matter of degree. Both think that in some instances rape is warranted. It is not.<br /><br />My sister is a social worker who works for child welfare. Recently she removed a 6 year old boy from foster care. The old lady he was living with physically abused him. He had been sleeping on the floor. I said to my boyfriend, if that child grows up to be a violent criminal, I could never blame him. I couldn't imagine the life he has led, the violence he has endured. We as a society are failing our children and then when they grow up and continue the cycle of violence, the only thing they have ever known, we react with shock and call for more violence. It is ridiculous, if you think about it.<br /><br />These are the things that I've been thinking about since reading <i>First Night of Summer</i>. This is a chilling story, filled with gruesome crimes that are part of many people's realities. Apart from being a satisfying thriller, the book also serves to raise awareness of how easily a life can be disrupted by violent crime.<br /><br />I would hesitate to recommend the book to those who struggle with descriptions of rape and torture. The scenes with the kidnapper made me very uncomfortable, but the actions are not described in as much detail as it could have been, for which I am grateful.<br /><br />At times I felt the scenes with Ricky became repetitive and gratuitous. I also didn't enjoy the ending. I would have liked to be left with some measure of hope that even in the face of unimaginable cruelty, humans can respond with mercy and kindness, but that didn't happen. Without a doubt, the ending here is probably more realistic and I'm certain that those who believe in "an eye for an eye" will find a tremendous amount of satisfaction here, but it left me cold.<br /><br />Overall I enjoyed the story and would recommend this book to fans of this genre.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2079603930128469624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


