<div id="review_1005268402" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1005268402" />
    <a title="Glenn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18345198-glenn"><img alt="Glenn" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1005268402?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Glenn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Glenn" href="/user/show/18345198-glenn">Glenn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1005268402" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5911598856076873007">I found this book on one of Goodreads&apos; lists, the topic being &quot;True Crime Involving young adults<br/>True crime reads that mainly focus on teens who have murdered or have been murdered&quot;<br/>That&apos;s exactly what I was looking for - true crime involving teenagers. From the description it sounded good, so trusting the ever-reliable Goodreads, I purchased the book. When I got the book the first thing I saw under the title was &quot;A Novel&quot;. Wait a minute. Wasn&apos;t this listed as &quot;true crime&quot;? Isn&apos;t that what I was l</span>
  <span id="freeText5911598856076873007" style="display:none">I found this book on one of Goodreads' lists, the topic being "True Crime Involving young adults<br />True crime reads that mainly focus on teens who have murdered or have been murdered"<br />That's exactly what I was looking for - true crime involving teenagers. From the description it sounded good, so trusting the ever-reliable Goodreads, I purchased the book. When I got the book the first thing I saw under the title was "A Novel". Wait a minute. Wasn't this listed as "true crime"? Isn't that what I was looking for? Something that really happened? Well, a novel is the exact opposite of true. It never happened. If you don't believe me look at the disclaimer in the front of every novel, including this one. The other part of the list title was true crime involving young adults - teenagers - who murder or get murdered.Well guess what? There is not one single teenager in this whole book. All of the characters are either little kids or full grown adults! I don't know how often Goodreads misrepresents books with lists that misfire on all cylinders. I was going to ask them to pay me back my purchase price. But the novel turned out to be so scary, so genuinely emotional, so suspenseful and so well written that I was really glad I got it. The novel's a stunner and it took courage to write the violence and horror that you can't look away from. This novel will terrify you and break your heart. Many times. If you like reading about serial killers, this book has one, and he feels terrifyingly real.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5911598856076873007" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


